#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:556
msgid "Array Iterators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:563
msgid ""
"Iterators are a powerful concept for array processing. Essentially, "
"iterators implement a generalized for-loop. If *myiter* is an iterator "
"object, then the Python code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:567
msgid ""
"for val in myiter:\n"
"    ...\n"
"    some code involving val\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:572
msgid ""
"calls ``val = next(myiter)`` repeatedly until :exc:`StopIteration` is raised "
"by the iterator. There are several ways to iterate over an array that may be "
"useful: default iteration, flat iteration, and :math:`N`-dimensional "
"enumeration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:579
msgid "Default iteration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:581
msgid ""
"The default iterator of an ndarray object is the default Python iterator of "
"a sequence type. Thus, when the array object itself is used as an iterator. "
"The default behavior is equivalent to::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:585
msgid ""
"for i in range(arr.shape[0]):\n"
"    val = arr[i]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:588
msgid ""
"This default iterator selects a sub-array of dimension :math:`N-1` from the "
"array. This can be a useful construct for defining recursive algorithms. To "
"loop over the entire array requires :math:`N` for-loops."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:604
msgid "Flat iteration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:610:<autosummary>:1
msgid ":py:obj:`ndarray.flat <numpy.ndarray.flat>`\\"
msgstr ":py:obj:`ndarray.flat <numpy.ndarray.flat>`\\"

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:610:<autosummary>:1
msgid "A 1-D iterator over the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:611
msgid ""
"As mentioned previously, the flat attribute of ndarray objects returns an "
"iterator that will cycle over the entire array in C-style contiguous order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:623
msgid ""
"Here, I've used the built-in enumerate iterator to return the iterator index "
"as well as the value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:628
msgid "N-dimensional enumeration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:634:<autosummary>:1
msgid ":py:obj:`ndenumerate <numpy.ndenumerate>`\\ \\(arr\\)"
msgstr ":py:obj:`ndenumerate <numpy.ndenumerate>`\\ \\(arr\\)"

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:634:<autosummary>:1
msgid "Multidimensional index iterator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:635
msgid ""
"Sometimes it may be useful to get the N-dimensional index while iterating. "
"The ndenumerate iterator can achieve this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:647
msgid "Iterator for broadcasting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:653:<autosummary>:1
msgid ":py:obj:`broadcast <numpy.broadcast>`\\"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:653:<autosummary>:1
msgid "Produce an object that mimics broadcasting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:654
msgid ""
"The general concept of broadcasting is also available from Python using the :"
"class:`broadcast` iterator. This object takes :math:`N` objects as inputs "
"and returns an iterator that returns tuples providing each of the input "
"sequence elements in the broadcasted result."
msgstr ""

